{"id":14881228,"mediaExerciseId":"cb706120-407e-4054-9912-0f58c7cd2e28","exerciseName":"4","chapterName":"10","chapterTitle":"Making Capital Investment Decisions","groupId":612341,"groupTitle":"Critical Thinking Questions","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":341,"solutions":[{"id":6274975,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this problem, we will discuss what the stand-alone principle is and what its implications are to project evaluations. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"The stand-alone principle is an evaluation method where each project is treated as its own mini firm with its own assets, liabilities, and revenues. Since it the project is considered as a mini firm, then the financial costs are considered. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"In evaluating projects, it is not advised to include the financial costs in the evaluation since these are already part of the capital of the project. If the financial costs are evaluated, then the capital is doubled which will affect the value of the company. This is a negative effect since if the capital is doubled, then the evaluation may show that the project is not profitable since it will be difficult to break even on the capital especially since it is now counted twice. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3}],"rating":0,"solutionUuid":"9f285bd7-f4d7-44cd-8c18-ee30d309c186","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":3},{"id":6388800,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"For this item, we are asked to evaluate the quoted statement above by a financial manager critically.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"At the corporate level, the manager can determine the company's financial position. Because one undertaking could have been altogether sponsored with capital appreciation and another with borrowed funds, and the company's actual financial leverage remains intact, lending rates are irrelevant in assessing an operation's accounting profit under the **stand-alone principle**.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2}],"rating":0,"solutionUuid":"cfcda70e-5642-4ef9-a782-4e353e8ddad8","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":2}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"9781259918957","isPremium":true,"title":"Fundamentals of Corporate Finance","edition":"12th Edition","verifiedSolutionCount":1217,"shouldBeIndexableForSeo":true,"modified":1665448474394,"active":true,"publisher":"McGraw-Hill Education","mainTextbookIsbn":null,"subjects":{"level1":["Social Science"],"level2":["Economics"],"level3":["Finance"]}},"nextExercises":[{"id":14881229,"exerciseName":"5","page":341,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"e56919ff-7356-4154-9f8c-1baf0367dff2","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-10-critical-thinking-questions-5-e56919ff-7356-4154-9f8c-1baf0367dff2"},{"id":14881230,"exerciseName":"6","page":341,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"529eec08-9efd-482f-bd73-0357d37358ea","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-97